Part 11

The telegram from Odisha was delivered to the Nandyal administrative office on a quiet Tuesday afternoon. It contained only four words: *Binay serious. Come home.*

Suresh had brought it into the room, his leather boots making a hurried, squeaking sound on the grey linoleum floor. 

Vikram didn't read the paper twice. He folded it slowly and stood up from his brown leatherette chair.

"Pack the project files, Suresh," he said, looking at the desk. "I am leaving."

"And the chair, sir?" Suresh asked, looking at the listing seat. "Should we send it by truck to the railway station so you have it in Calcutta?"

Vikram looked at the cracked armrest where the black tape had started peeling away to show the grey foam inside. 

"No," Vikram said. "Leave it here. Let someone else sit in it."

He took his small leather bag—the same suitcase he had brought with him five years ago—and walked out to the waiting ambassador car.

---

The family house in Odisha was silent. 

Binay was in the upstairs bedroom, the one that looked out over the kitchen garden. He was propped up on two flat pillows, his breathing shallow and rapid, with the yellow jaundice showing deep in the whites of his half-closed eyes.

Rohan was sitting on the wooden stool near the window. His shoes were clean today, but he kept his hands in his pockets, his shoulders hunched as he watched Vikram enter the room. 

Rohan did not stand up to greet him. "You took your time," he said, his voice flat.

"The train was delayed at Khurda junction," Vikram said, walking to the bed.

He sat on the wooden edge of the mattress. Binay's hand on the sheet was dry and cold; the skin felt like loose parchment, the veins rising blue and stiff against the bone.

The old man opened his eyes slowly, looking at Vikram first, and then at Rohan near the window. "The Nandyal plant..." Binay whispered, his voice barely a rasp.

"It is running, Papa," Vikram said, holding his fingers. "The bottling unit is complete. The first shipments have gone out."

Binay nodded once, his eyelids closing again under the weight of the illness. "Rohan," he said, his voice dry.

Rohan stood up from his stool, but he did not come to the bedside. He stayed near the dark wooden wardrobe. "Yes, Papa."

"The company... it is yours now. Both of you," the old man said.

Rohan looked down at the floorboards. "Vikram runs the board, Papa. I am just a site engineer."

Binay did not answer. He had already gone back to that quiet, unmoving state where the words of his sons could no longer reach him.

---

Vikram stood up and walked to the window. 

Down in the kitchen garden, Ramu, the old gardener, was collecting dry neem leaves in a bamboo basket, the leaves crackling softly as he swept.

Rohan looked out at the garden beside him, his voice low and tight. "You should have stayed at the head office. Reddy says you did all the work in the South. He says the board only wants your signature on the expansions."

"The signature is just ink on paper, Rohan," Vikram said.

"It is not," Rohan said, turning his back to the window. "It is what decides whose name goes on the gate."

He walked out of the room. His footsteps were loud on the wooden stairs, fading away until only the slow, heavy breathing of their father remained in the quiet room.

Vikram sat back on the edge of the bed and held the old man's cold hand. 

The room smelled of barley water, old linen, and the rubbing alcohol the nurse used for the thermometer. Outside, the sun was setting behind the kitchen garden, casting the shadows of the neem trees long and dark over the compost pit.

He knew this was the last week. He knew the white coat of the doctor was gone forever, and the company was all that remained of his father's expectations. 

But as he held his father's cold hand in the dark room, the fourteen hundred crore felt like nothing but a number written on a wall that was about to fall down.

